{{italic title}} {{Infobox European case |court=ECtHR |SubmitDate= |SubmitYear= 1987 |DecideDate= 26 October |DecideYear= 1988 |FullName= ''David Norris v. Ireland'' |CelexID= |CaseType= |CaseNumber=6/1987/129/180 |Chamber= |Nationality= [[Courts of the Republic of Ireland|Irish]] |Procedural= |Ruling= |JudgeRapporteur= |JudgePresident=R. Ryssdal |Judge1= J. Cremona |Judge2= Thór Vilhjálmsson |Judge3= F. Gölcüklü |Judge4= F. Matscher |Judge5= L.-E. Pettiti |Judge6= Brian Walsh (judge) |Judge7= Vincent Evans |Judge8= C. Russo |Judge9= R. Bernhardt |Judge10= A. Spielmann |Judge11= Jan de Meyer |Judge12= J.A. Carrillo Salcedo |Judge13= N. Valticos |AdvocateGeneral= |InstrumentsCited= |LegislationAffecting= * [[Article 8 of the European Convention on Human Rights]] * [[Criminal Law Amendment Act 1885]] * [[Offences against the Person Act 1861]] * [[Dudgeon v United Kingdom]] |Keywords= }}
'''''Norris v. Ireland''''' was a case decided by the [[European Court of Human Rights]] (ECHR) in 1988, in which [[David Norris (politician)|David Norris]] successfully charged that [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]'s criminalisation of certain homosexual acts between consenting adult men was in breach of [[Article 8 of the European Convention on Human Rights]] (right to respect for private and family life).
== Original case == {{main article|Norris v. Attorney General}} The original case in the [[Courts of the Republic of Ireland|Irish courts]] was [[Norris v. Attorney General]], introduced in 1977 and decided by the [[Supreme Court (Ireland)|Supreme Court of Ireland]] in 1983. Norris's [[Senior Counsel]] was fellow member of the [[Campaign for Homosexual Law Reform]], [[Mary Robinson]], who in 1990 would become the first female [[President of Ireland]]. The Irish courts ruled that Norris's [[right to privacy]] was not violated by the [[Offences against the Person Act 1861]] (criminalising "[[buggery]]") and the [[Criminal Law Amendment Act 1885]] (criminalising "[[Labouchere Amendment|gross indecency]]").
== Case before the ECtHR == Norris appealed the Irish court's decision to the ECtHR in 1983. The Court passed judgment in 1988, deciding in Norris's favour on grounds similar to those of its 1981 decision in ''[[Dudgeon v United Kingdom]]''.
The laws impugned by the judgment were eventually repealed by the Criminal Law (Sexual Offences) Act, 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://debates.oireachtas.ie/dail/1993/06/23/00021.asp|title=Private Members' Business. - Criminal Law (Sexual Offences) Bill, 1993: Second Stage.|date=23 June 1993|work=Dáil Éireann debates|publisher=Oireachtas|accessdate=9 July 2012|quote=it is the case that the main sections of the Bill arise against a background of the European Court decision in the Norris case}}</ref><ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1993/en/act/pub/0020/ Criminal Law (Sexual Offences) Act, 1993] [[Irish Statute Book]]</ref>
