In the [[Roman Catholic]] church, a '''''positio''''' (''Positio super Virtutibus'')  is a document or collection of documents used in the process by which a person is declared [[Venerable]], the second of the four steps on the path to Roman Catholic sainthood.  It collects the evidence obtained by a diocesan inquiry into a candidate's [[heroic virtue]]s in a form suitable for presentation to the [[Congregation for the Causes of Saints]].  Upon presentation, the ''positio'' is examined by a committee of expert historians and theologians, and if they find the evidence presented suitable, they may then make a recommendation to the Pope that the candidate be declared Venerable.

''Positios'' can run to over 1,000 pages in length.  The time between the preparation of a ''positio'' and a recommendation by the committee of historians and theologians can often be measured in decades.

